{"key":"post-9827911","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>9827911</id>\n<content>100% humidity does not cause water droplets to form on the fruits.&amp;nbsp; Having 100% humidity and THEN adding more moisture causes water droplets to form on fruits and every thing else.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A bit of moisture after misting is fine, but you don't want to have water just sitting on the fruits and not going anywhere.&amp;nbsp; That's where air exchange comes in.&amp;nbsp; You want constant fresh air, thus there is also a constant loss of moisture from the substrate.&amp;nbsp; This will cause any water droplets on the fruits to evaporate off.&amp;nbsp; Let the substrate dry out for a few hours, and then mist again.&amp;nbsp; This ebb and flow of moisture content is a major pinning trigger.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>9827924</next>\n<prev>9827822</prev>\n<first>9825953</first>\n<last>9828198</last>\n<when>1235088990</when>\n<utime>02/20/09 02:16 AM</utime>\n</post>"}